content.description: Slabby climbing the center of the cliff. Use decent sloppy holds till you hit the thanks god jugs at the top.
content.protection: Very poor landing.  At least 3 pads and two spotters.  With out them a fall will leave you tumbling 50 feet down the hill and probably earn you an expensive trip to the hospital.
content.location: As you are looking at Doughnuts for James, head left 30 yards.  This heads up the center of the cliff

content.description: Stay within the black streak.  If you step outside of it, you arent doing this route.  Start on the large hold, reach for the right hand pinch and high step.  Next, head towards the pocket with a left hand and figure the rest out from there.

A nice little crack that heads left to some scary blocks which may or may not be loose.  Pull on them carefully but don't place protection on them.  A fun little romp! 

  First lead on-site by Andy McMurray with two pieces of protection, neither of which was small enough for the crack or safe enough to hold a fall (hence the name).
content.protection: The lower crack will take C3s or nuts.  Higher up you can plug a #1 Camalot.  Walk off or rap from the anchors on PB or GB.
content.location: To the right of Grandma Bubbles - kind of the arete on the main face but follows a thin crack system

content.description: This route begins to the left of the obvious black streak.  Work upwards.
content.location: From "Doughnuts for James" (#6 on the hand drawn map) hike up the hill to the left.  Passing the large boulder with a crappy landing on the right, you will arrive at the "flat landing boulder".  There are three routes on it.

content.description: SDS on sharp crimps on the arete to the right of Foxy Lady.  Follow the arete to the top out.  All face holds are off.
content.location: To the right of Foxy Lady

content.description: Not a bad crack for a quick fix!  If this started from the ground it would be a boulder problem - but the ledge it starts from is 15 feet up so the fall would be big.  Easy first lead and good for learning how to place cams and hexes...we might use this one to teach!   This would have had a vile name if Andy had done it first...established on rope solo.
content.location: In a dihedral to the right of Grandma Bubbles.

content.description: Start the same as Pandora's Box but hang a right at the crux.  The name says it all!  Not a hard climb but the protection sucks!
content.protection: Not much until you are near the top!

content.description: First climbed ground up trad in 2007 with sketchy protection but has had two bolts (plus anchors) added to protect the crux.   This was originally rated 5.7 then 5.8 but people whined and suggested 5.10 (BS!) so we rated it 5.9 so as not to sandbag too badly.  It's a good safe lead now...   Solid start to a sequency and balancy crux that asks you to bear down hard on a crimp.  Follow the water groove up using the crimp to a side pull and then shoot for the horn!  Climb mellows above for 15/20 feet to the anchors.
content.protection: 2 bolts plus a few cams or nuts from #00 to #.75

content.description: A few ledges then up to a large bulge 10 feet off the deck with poor holds.  Get out there and send this.  Crux is pulling the bulge and toping out. Grade is approximate, you send it and let me know.
content.protection: At least 3 pads and a couple spotters.
content.location: Just to the right of Foxxy Lady and Quick Fix Crack as you come up the trail.

content.description: Sweet slab climb on dime edges with a sloper mantle on top...There are a few horizontal cracks to make it easier if need be...but you should avoid them for style points!
What could be an amazing climb fizzles after 8 feet!  Splitter crack in a dihedral and then pretty boring 5.1 climbing.  Could be a good first lead for someone who is really new!  Not a bad solo...
content.location: Between Golgatha's Chimney and Pandora's Box on Fox Face.

content.description:
V2ish boulder problem at the bottom with no protection until you are 10 feet up.  The climb mellows quickly with good protection.  Has seen two leads, two solos and a hand full of TR ascents.  Stout route and destined to be a D-Town mini classic. 

  There are now permanent anchors at the top of this climb.
The route is chossy and may be easier using roots shrubs as aid.  The crux is mental as you hope not to fall back upon the steep approach.
content.protection: Pro is not necessary but a spotter would be helpful if attempting any stylish moves up the route other than just getting up it as quickly and safely as possible.
content.location: An alternate access chimney to the top of the Foxx Rocks climbs.  It is located climbers right of the crag, past Quick Fix Crack.

content.description: Standing start on invisible crimps to a side pull.  Bump your feet up and gun for the topout.
content.location: Foxx Face just below Quick Fix Crack on the obvious 15 degree face.

content.description: This line follows the crack the whole way, anything outside the crack is off. Sit start to obvious crimp and crack next to it,up to the small crimp up and right off of the crack then to top.
content.location: To the far left of the black streak, follow Y crack on the right to the top.

content.description: Start on the left side of the boulder on a crimp.  Figure out the feet (be creative) and reach up for a left handed undercling.  Get here and you're as good as done with it.
content.location: "Flat landing boulder"  uphill from "Doughnuts for James".

content.description: SDS for donuts for James on decent holds and poor feet.  Pull your butt off the ground and bump your right hadn straight up to the slopper.  Move into the double underclings and finish the same as Donuts for James.  Adds a lot of difficulty
Up the center of this boulder/cliff band. Undercling, step up and dyno for the rail.
content.location: East Walls. This is the furthest East cliff band on the North side of Haines Rd.

content.description: Finger crack below Quick fix crack and to the left of Foxxy Lady.  Probably 5.9 and could be combined with quick fix crack if you are really desperate in get new climbing in.
Pinch, pull and crimp your way up the face
content.location: Lower Fox Rock, to the left of the obvious dihedral with a finger crack.

content.description:
Foxx Rocks is a collection of two small outcroppings and one larger cliff - Lower Fox Rock, Upper Fox Rock and Fox Face.  Lower Fox Rock is up to 20 feet tall and features a few highball bouldering problems...only one of which has been done yet.  It will require more cleaning and a developement session.  Upper Fox Rock features a single slab problem and possible potential for someone with vision.  Fox Face holds a few bouldering problems and 7 or 8 roped routes from 16 feet to 40 feet tall.  The best routes to date on this side are Pandora's Box (5.9+) and Grandma Bubbles (5.11a R). 

  There are now permanent anchors on Pandora's Box and Grandma Bubbles.  Please use your own draws and biners to extend the life of the anchors!   Thanks...
